---
title: "Why Every Custom Software Project Needs a Private Repo and a Live Staging Link"
date: "2024-04-22"
summary: "Every custom software project needs a private repository and a live staging link from day one. Protect your code and show your progress."
coverImage: ""
tags:
  - "Development"
author: "Redevise"
---

Your developer stores code on their laptop. There is no backup. There is no version history. There is no way for you to see the work.

A private repository is a version-controlled code store. Git. Private. Accessible to the client and the developer. Every change is tracked. Every version is saved. If the developer's laptop dies, the code survives.

A live staging link is a URL where the client can see the working software. Not a screenshot. Not a demo. The actual software. Updated regularly. The client can click through. Test features. See progress.

Here is why both matter.

The repo protects your investment. If the relationship with the developer ends, you have the code. You can give it to another developer. Without the repo, you have nothing.

The staging link protects your expectations. You see the software as it is built. Not as it will be in six months. You catch misunderstandings early. When they are cheap to fix.

I took over a project in 2024 where the previous developer had no repo. The code was on a laptop. The laptop was lost. The project had to be rebuilt. The cost was $45,000.

A repo would have cost $0. A staging link would have cost $10 a month. The savings would have been $45,000.

Set up the repo before development starts. Deploy the staging link after the first sprint. The cost is minimal. The protection is total.
